Headlines.SeoHeadline: Archstone Sale Means Lost IPO Fees for Citi, JPM
Headlines.Author: Telis Demos
Headlines.Headline: Archstone Sale Means Lost IPO Fees for Citi, JPM

PARAGRAPH.#text: Archstone’s about-face from initial public offering to sale isn’t happy news for banks on track to lead the offering.Citigroup Inc. and J.P. Morgan Chase & Co. were in line to lead Archstone’s IPO. They would have been the largest recipients in a fee pool in the neighborhood of $100 million, based on the size of Archstone’s planned offering.The offering, expected to raise $3.5 billion, was on track to be the largest offering ever by a real-estate investment trust, according to Dealogic, and the third-largest U.S.-listed IPO of any kind this year.Spokespeople for Citi and J.P. Morgan declined to comment.Now, Archstone’s IPO bankers will have to contend for other roles. Already, some key jobs have been nabbed by others. Equity sales by Avalon Bay and Equity Residential to pay for the cash component of the deal are being led by Goldman Sachs Group Inc. and Morgan Stanley, respectively, according to filings with regulators.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Archstone Sale Means Lost IPO Fees for Citi, JPM

Headlines.Author: Kristin Jones
Headlines.Headline: Equity Residential Third-Quarter Net Surges on Rents, Gains

PARAGRAPH.#text: Equity Residential's EQR third-quarter profit more than doubled as the real-estate investment trust reported higher rental income as well as one-time gains. The company also raised its full-year outlook for normalized funds from operations, a key measure of profitability in the real estate sector. It now sees FFO of $2.74 to $2.78 a share, compared with its previous guidance of $2.73 to $2.78 a share. For the current quarter, the company expects FFO of 72 cents to 76 cents a share, shy of the 78 cents a share FFO seen by analysts recently polled by Thomson Reuters.

Headlines.Headline: EARNINGS PREVIEW: U.S. Multifamily REITs Still See High Occupancy, Rents

PARAGRAPH.#text: TAKING THE PULSE: Some of the same trends that have impeded U.S. homeownership since the recession--including a shaky recovery and skepticism about the market--have fed demand for rental housing. Real-estate investment trusts with a focus on multifamily housing have been the primary beneficiaries, recording high occupancy rates and high rents. This trend looks likely to continue in the near term and has driven a drumbeat of recent housing-property acquisitions. SNL Financial noted that New York and California have attracted the most investment, as UDR Inc. (UDR), Equity Residential (EQR) and others seek to capitalize on the markets that feature the highest rents.

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. confirmed its will buy the 26.5% stake in Archstone it doesn't already own for $1.58 billion, ending a high-stakes battle over the control of the apartment giant. The Wall Street Journal late Thursday reported the failed investment bank, which emerged from bankruptcy under a liquidation plan earlier this year, planned to buy the stake from Bank of America Corp. BAC and Barclays PLC BCS, which together partnered with Lehman to buy Archstone in a 2007 leveraged buyout valued at $22 billion.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: Morning MarketBeat: Bernanke Takes The Stage
Headlines.Author: Dave Kansas
Headlines.Headline: Morning MarketBeat: Bernanke Takes The Stage

PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:Market Tone: Cautious ahead of Bernanke press conference. Dollar mixed, Treasurys lower, oil slightly higher, gold little changedOvernight Action: BP Net Profit Rises; S&P Changes Japan Outlook to Negative;Watch for: Fed rate decision and press conference,  earnings from Ebay, Starbucks, Boeing, ConocoPhillipsThe Breakfast BriefingToday, all eyes will go to the Bearded One.Federal Reserve Chairman Ben Bernanke will face the scribes in a first-ever press conference at 2:15 p.m. EDT. The Fed says the press conference is aimed at increasing transparency. It?s more likely to be a tour de force in sleep-inducing obfuscation.The Federal Open Market Committee, the Fed?s policy group, will issue its statement at 1230 p.m. EDT, ahead of Big Ben?s 2:15 p.m. EDT date with the press. It is difficult to imagine that Big Ben will break new ground at the microphone, but there?s always hope. Jean-Claude Trichet, head of the European Central Bank, used a press briefing to signal that the ECB planned to raise rates this month, which it did early this month. (The ECB, like other central banks, has held press briefings for years.)The dollar?s recent weakness ? the dollar index is at a three-year low and the euro is at a fresh 52-week high ? underscores the belief that the Fed is in no rush to tighten its extraordinarily loose monetary policy. Our friends at Real Time Economics offer a nifty primer on how to interpret the words and phrases of Big Ben. (The over/under betting line for number of chuckles Big Ben gets: three.)The Fed, in its statement, is expected to say it will finish its $600 billion quantitative easing program (QE2) on schedule in June. It is also not expected to raise too many alarms about looming interest-rate moves. The Fed-funds futures sees only a 26% chance that the Fed will raise rates to 0.5% by next February.As investors fidget about what the Bearded One might say, earnings will come in full force once again. On Tuesday, strong earnings from 3M, Ford Motor, Delta Air Lines and UPS helped set a robust tone from the opening bell.The Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 115.49 to 12595.37, its highest close since June 5, 2008. The Nasdaq Composite jumped 21.66 to 2847.54, its highest close since Oct. 31, 2007. And the S&P 500 gained 11.99 to 1347.24, its best close since June 17, 2008.On Wednesday, earnings will come from all directions, with energy and aerospace dominating.On the energy front, Baker Hughes, Cabot Oil & Gas, BP, ConocoPhillips, ENI, Hess Corp. and National Oil Well Varco report. Energy companies have reported strong earnings, boosted by rising oil prices. Boeing, General Dynamics and Northrop Grumman report on the aerospace side. Lockheed Martin reported solid earnings Tuesday; its shares rose more than 2%.Other notable earnings: Norfolk Southern, Whirlpool, Las Vegas Sands, Akamai, Baidu, Dr. Pepper Snapple, Green Mountain Coffee Roasters, eBay, Credit Suisse, Southern Co., and Barrick Gold. (A fuller list of key earnings due today are down below.)On the economic front, March durable goods orders are expected to show a 2.4% gain, reversing an unexpected decline in February. Also, the Energy Department reports petroleum data mid-morning. Crude oil stocks are expected to rise 1.1 million barrels and gasoline stocks are expected to decline once again. (A complete list of G7 economic reports due on Wednesday is at the end of this post.)The market surge on Tuesday had some chin-scratchers arguing that investors were buying the rumor (Bernanke will be really soft/nice/kind/luvy-duvy) in anticipation of selling that news (the actual statement/press briefing). PARAGRAPH.#text: Ed Durkin, a union official, is on a mission. He says that board members at U.S. corporations who are seeking re-election should be required to win more than 50% of the vote to retain their seats. His group's campaign is just one of the many shareholder initiatives that will be debated across the land this spring as public companies prepare for annual meeting season. PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds quote from Rent.com, updates stock prices.) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--With many Americans boomeranging back to Mom and Dad's or sharing digs with roommates, the nation's apartment operators, particularly the public players, continue to bite their nails as they await recovery. The Pew Research Center reports that 1 in 10 adults ages 18 to 35, prime renting years, say the weak economy has forced them to return to the nest. Headlines.Headline: Sam Zell: Sees No Real Estate Opportunities In US, Europe

PARAGRAPH.#text: LONDON (Dow Jones)--U.S. real estate entrepreneur Sam Zell said Tuesday he sees no significant opportunities in the European or U.S. property markets. Zell, who is chairman of Equity Group Investments, said "as an equity investor I see little opportunity in the U.S. and even less in Europe," advising investors instead to look to emerging markets for growth. Speaking at the real estate investment trust forum run by NAREIT, the U.S. real estate investment trust, or REIT, association, in London, Zell said he expects European property values to fall and he is identifying opportunities in Mexico, Chile, Brazil and China instead.

    results will fall short of expectations. The manufacturer of embedded computers expects a
    profit of 38 to 40 cents a share in the first quarter on revenue of $1 million to $1.5
    million. Radisys expects its second quarter to be "solidly profitable" with
    sales in the range of $28 million to $30 million. Prior to the announcement, the consensus
    estimate was 49 cents a share for the first quarter and 54 cents a share in the second
    quarter. Radisys said several customers have postponed or reduced orders, while its
    largest customer expects to place no orders in the second quarter amid excess inventory
    and slackening demand. "I also expect some weakness to carry into the third
    quarter," said Glen Myers, chief executive officer. Myers cited the large revenue
    decline and weaker-than-anticipated orders from chip equipment and contract manufacturing
    customers. However, Myers expects moderate order recovery in the third quarter to push
    revenue back into the $33-million to $37-million range. Shares closed down 1/4 at 31 5/8.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Radisys sees rocky first half

Headlines.Headline: Microsoft, Sun Java hearing begins

#text: Shares of both Sun Microsystems (SUNW)
and Microsoft (MSFT)

rose
    slightly Friday afternoon as the first court hearing in Sun's Java lawsuit began in San
    Jose, Calif. Sun filed the suit last October, seeking a preliminary injunction to bar
    Microsoft from using the "Java compatible" logo. According to Sun, Microsoft
    software isn't compatible with the programming language. Separately,Microsoft CEO
    Bill Gates is expected to appear next week at a Senate panel hearing examining market
    power in the software industry. Sun Microsystems CEO Scott McNealy and Netscape
    Communications (NSCP)

CEO Jim Barksdale also have confirmed their attendance at the Tuesday session, a Judiciary
    Committee spokeswoman said. She said other industry representatives would also testify. 
    Microsoft shares closed up 1/2 to 85 7/16. Sun shares rose 3/8 to 47 3/8.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Microsoft, Sun Java hearing begins
